# Plan: Add `mistral-instruct-v3` Specialized Chat Template Handler

## Context

`common/chat.cpp` routes Jinja-based chat templates to specialized handlers that know how to build PEG parsers for their specific output format. Currently, Mistral templates that use `[SYSTEM_PROMPT]` (Ministral/Mistral Large 3) are handled, but plain Mistral Instruct v0.3 templates — which use `[INST]/[/INST]` markers, prepend the system message to the first user turn, and emit `</s>` after assistant turns — fall through to the generic autoparser. This adds a dedicated handler and detection case so those templates get precise PEG parsing.

---

## Constraint

**Only add new code.** Do not modify any existing handler functions or `chat.h`.

---

## Critical Files

| File | Purpose |
|---|---|
| `common/chat.cpp` | Only file to be changed. Add new handler function and one new `if`-block in the detection function. |
| `models/templates/mistralai-Mistral-Nemo-Instruct-2407.jinja` | Reference template: uses `[INST]`, no `[SYSTEM_PROMPT]`; confirms what output the PEG parser must match. |

---

## Step-by-Step Implementation

### Step 1 — Add the handler function in `common/chat.cpp`

Insert immediately before `common_chat_try_specialized_template` (currently starting at line 1634), after the closing `}` of `common_chat_params_init_gigachat_v3` (line 1517).

```cpp
static common_chat_params common_chat_params_init_mistral_instruct_v3(
    const common_chat_template &          tmpl,
    const autoparser::generation_params & inputs) {
    common_chat_params data;

    data.prompt           = common_chat_template_direct_apply_impl(tmpl, inputs);
    data.format           = COMMON_CHAT_FORMAT_PEG_NATIVE;
    data.preserved_tokens = { "[INST]", "[/INST]" };

    auto has_tools       = inputs.tools.is_array() && !inputs.tools.empty();
    auto include_grammar = has_tools && inputs.tool_choice != COMMON_CHAT_TOOL_CHOICE_NONE;

    auto parser = build_chat_peg_parser([&](common_chat_peg_builder & p) {
        // Tool-call format: [TOOL_CALLS][{"name":"…","arguments":{…},"id":"…"}]</s>
        if (has_tools && inputs.tool_choice != COMMON_CHAT_TOOL_CHOICE_NONE) {
            auto tool_choice = p.choice();
            foreach_function(inputs.tools, [&](const json & tool) {
                const auto & function = tool.at("function");
                std::string  name     = function.at("name");
                const auto & schema   = function.at("parameters");
                auto tool_name = p.json_member("name", "\"" + p.tool_name(p.literal(name)) + "\"");
                auto tool_args = p.json_member("arguments", p.tool_args(p.schema(p.json(), "tool-" + name + "-schema", schema)));
                auto tool_open = p.tool_open(p.literal("{") << tool_name);
                tool_choice |= p.rule("tool-" + name, tool_open << "," << tool_args << "}");
            });
            auto min_calls  = inputs.tool_choice == COMMON_CHAT_TOOL_CHOICE_REQUIRED ? 1 : 0;
            auto max_calls  = inputs.parallel_tool_calls ? -1 : 1;
            auto tool_calls = p.trigger_rule("tool-call",
                p.literal("[TOOL_CALLS][") +
                p.repeat(tool_choice, min_calls, max_calls) +
                p.literal("]"));
            return p.prefix(inputs.generation_prompt) +
                   (p.content(p.until("[TOOL_CALLS]")) << tool_calls);
        }
        // Content-only: assistant text runs to end of generation
        include_grammar = false;
        return p.prefix(inputs.generation_prompt) + p.content(p.rest());
    });

    data.parser = parser.save();

    if (include_grammar) {
        data.grammar_lazy = inputs.tool_choice == COMMON_CHAT_TOOL_CHOICE_AUTO;
        data.grammar = build_grammar([&](const common_grammar_builder & builder) {
            foreach_function(inputs.tools, [&](const json & tool) {
                const auto & function = tool.at("function");
                auto schema = function.at("parameters");
                builder.resolve_refs(schema);
            });
            parser.build_grammar(builder, data.grammar_lazy);
        });
        data.grammar_triggers = {
            { COMMON_GRAMMAR_TRIGGER_TYPE_WORD, "[TOOL_CALLS]" }
        };
    }

    return data;
}
```

**Key design decisions:**
- `data.prompt` is produced by the existing Jinja engine — no manual formatting.
- `preserved_tokens` keeps `[INST]`/`[/INST]` from being split during tokenization (mirrors how other Mistral handlers treat their special tokens).
- Tool-call parsing mirrors `common_chat_params_init_gigachat_v3` (JSON object with named members), adapted to the `[TOOL_CALLS][…]` array wrapper used by the v3 format.
- Content-only path sets `include_grammar = false`, exactly as done in Ministral and GigaChatV3 handlers.

---

### Step 2 — Add detection case in `common_chat_try_specialized_template`

Append the following block inside `common_chat_try_specialized_template` (currently line 1634–1691), just **before** the final `return std::nullopt` at line 1690:

```cpp
    // Mistral Instruct v0.3 — [INST]/[/INST] markers without [SYSTEM_PROMPT].
    // [SYSTEM_PROMPT] would indicate Ministral/Mistral Large 3 (already handled above).
    if (src.find("[INST]") != std::string::npos &&
        src.find("[SYSTEM_PROMPT]") == std::string::npos) {
        LOG_DBG("Using specialized template: mistral-instruct-v3\n");
        return common_chat_params_init_mistral_instruct_v3(tmpl, params);
    }
```

**Why this placement and condition works:**
- The Ministral 3 check (line 1640) runs first and requires `[SYSTEM_PROMPT]` — it will consume any Ministral template before this check fires.
- The Mistral v7 template also contains `[SYSTEM_PROMPT]`, so it is similarly excluded.
- None of the other currently detected templates (`<|channel|>`, `>>>all`, `<|tool_calls_section_begin|>`, etc.) use `[INST]`, so ordering relative to them is safe.
- Placing this last (just before `return std::nullopt`) avoids accidentally capturing exotic templates that happen to contain `[INST]` as a substring before any more-specific handler could have matched.

---

## What is NOT changed

- `common/chat.h` — no new declarations required; the new function is `static` and only called from within `chat.cpp`.
- All existing handler functions (`common_chat_params_init_ministral_3`, `_gpt_oss`, `_functionary_v3_2`, `_kimi_k2`, `_lfm2`, `_lfm2_5`, `_gigachat_v3`) — untouched.
- `src/llama-chat.cpp` / `src/llama-chat.h` — the older C-level enum-based template system; unrelated to this change.

---

## Verification

1. **Targeted template detection**: Load the `mistralai-Mistral-Nemo-Instruct-2407.jinja` template (it has `[INST]` and no `[SYSTEM_PROMPT]`). Check the debug log for `"Using specialized template: mistral-instruct-v3"`.
2. **Ministral not displaced**: Load `mistralai-Ministral-3-14B-Reasoning-2512.jinja`. Debug log must still show `"Using specialized template: Ministral/Magistral Large 3"` — proving the ordering is correct.
3. **Content-only output**: A single user turn with no tools should produce a `common_chat_params` whose `format` is `COMMON_CHAT_FORMAT_PEG_NATIVE` and whose `grammar` is empty.
4. **Tool call output**: With tools and `tool_choice=auto`, the grammar and `grammar_triggers` fields must be populated, and the PEG parser's `parser` field must be non-empty.
5. **Run existing test suite**: `tests/test-chat-template.cpp` should pass without modification. If a test exercises the Nemo template it will now exercise the new handler path; no expected-output strings should change because the Jinja-rendered `prompt` is unchanged.

